If it is allowed to use regular expressions for this task, the following solution may be suggested (somewhat similar to [that of @Cary Swoveland](https://stackoverflow.com/a/71272964/13279831)) with some changes:
1) validate the format of the tag to be `DDXDDD-DD`, where `D` is a non-zero digit, `X` is a consonant  
This can be done using a positive lookahead:  
`(?=[1-9]{2}[B-Z&amp;&amp;[^EIOUY]][1-9]{3}-[1-9]{2})`  
where `[B-Z&amp;&amp;[^EIOUY]]` is a range of capital letters `B-Z` _except for_ vowels `[^EIOUY]` (`A` is excluded)

2) check the pairs of digit NOT to contain mix of odd and even digits:
```java
public static String isValid(String str) {
    return str.matches(&quot;(?=[1-9]{2}[B-Z&amp;&amp;[^EIOUY]][1-9]{3}-[1-9]{2})((?!.*(?:[2468][13579]|[13579][2468]))\\d{2,3}[-B-Z&amp;&amp;[^EIOUY]]?){3}&quot;)
        ? &quot;valid&quot;
        : &quot;invalid&quot;;
}
```
----
Checking for the sum of two consecutive digits to be even may be implemented as follows:
```java
public static String isValid(String str) {
    boolean hasValidFormat = str.matches(&quot;\\[1-9]][B-Z&amp;&amp;[^EIOUY]][1-9]{3}-[1-9]{2}&quot;);
    if (hasValidFormat) {
        out: for (String part : str.split(&quot;\\D&quot;)) {
            int firstDigit = Character.getNumericValue(part.charAt(0));
            for (int i = 1; i &lt; part.length(); i++) {
                int digit = Character.getNumericValue(part.charAt(i));
                if ((digit + firstDigit) % 2 != 0) {
                    hasValidFormat = false;
                    break out;
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return hasValidFormat ? &quot;valid&quot; : &quot;invalid&quot;;
}
```
